## 6. Shield Flow — Public → Private

**Shield** = move tokens from your public wallet (0x address) into the RAILGUN system (encrypted UTXOs).

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User as User
    participant UI as ShieldDialog.tsx
    participant TX as transactions.ts
    participant Engine as RAILGUN Engine
    participant ARB as Arbitrum

    User->>UI: Click "Shield 100 USDC"
    UI->>TX: buildShieldTransaction({ tokenAddress, amount, fromAddress })
    TX->>Engine: ensureEngineReady()
    TX->>Engine: populateShield(V2_PoseidonMerkle, "Arbitrum", shieldKey, recipients, [])

    Note over Engine: What happens inside populateShield:
    Note over Engine: 1. Generate random shieldPrivateKey (32 bytes)
    Note over Engine: 2. Compute commitment = Poseidon(amount, token, recipientPubKey, random)
    Note over Engine: 3. Build transaction to RAILGUN proxy contract
    Note over Engine: NO PROOF NEEDED for shield (it's a public → private deposit)

    Engine-->>TX: { to: "0xFA7...", data: "0x...", value: 0 }
    TX-->>UI: Raw transaction
    UI->>User: "Approve USDC + Confirm Shield"

    User->>ARB: Step 1: USDC.approve(RAILGUN_PROXY, 100e6)
    User->>ARB: Step 2: Submit shield transaction

    Note over ARB: RAILGUN contract:
    Note over ARB: 1. Pulls 100 USDC from user
    Note over ARB: 2. Creates encrypted UTXO commitment
    Note over ARB: 3. Inserts commitment into Poseidon Merkle tree
    Note over ARB: 4. Emits Shield event (encrypted — only recipient can decode)
```

### Why shielding does NOT require a Groth16 proof:

Shielding is a **public** operation — the blockchain can see "100 USDC was deposited into RAILGUN by 0xABC". No privacy needs to be proven at this stage. The privacy starts when those shielded funds are spent.

> [!NOTE]
> After shielding, funds are in **"ShieldPending"** status on Arbitrum. They move to **"Spendable"** only after POI (Proof of Innocence) validation completes — usually a few minutes. See [Section 10](#10-proof-of-innocence).

---

## 7. Unshield Flow — Private → Public

**Unshield** = move tokens from RAILGUN (encrypted UTXOs) back to a public wallet. **This is where the Groth16 proof is critical.**

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User as User
    participant UI as UnshieldDialog.tsx
    participant TX as transactions.ts
    participant Prover as snarkjs Prover
    participant Engine as RAILGUN Engine
    participant ARB as Arbitrum

    User->>UI: Click "Unshield 50 USDC to 0xDEF..."
    UI->>TX: buildUnshieldTransaction(req, walletId, encKey, "Arbitrum")
    TX->>Engine: ensureEngineReady()
    TX->>TX: triggerBalanceScan(walletId, 42161)
    Note over TX: Refresh Merkle tree so proof uses latest state

    TX->>Engine: ensureProverInitialized()
    Note over Engine: Load snarkjs WASM + patch fullProve()

    TX->>TX: clearArtifactMemoryCache()
    Note over TX: Force fresh artifact load from IndexedDB

    TX->>TX: Acquire unshieldMutex (prevent concurrent proofs)

    TX->>Engine: gasEstimateForUnprovenUnshield(...)
    Engine-->>TX: gasEstimate: 800_000n

    Note over TX,Prover: === PROOF GENERATION STARTS ===

    TX->>Engine: generateUnshieldProof(V2_PoseidonMerkle, "Arbitrum", walletId, ...)

    Note over Engine,Prover: Inside generateUnshieldProof:
    Note over Engine: 1. Find UTXO(s) with enough balance
    Note over Engine: 2. Compute Merkle path for each UTXO
    Note over Engine: 3. Compute nullifiers (mark UTXOs as spent)
    Note over Engine: 4. Compute output commitments (change UTXO, if any)
    Note over Prover: 5. snarkjs.groth16.fullProve(witness, circuit.wasm, proving_key.zkey)
    Note over Prover: ↑ This is the expensive step: 5-30 seconds
    Note over Prover: 6. Output: proof π (A, B, C points on BN128 curve)
    Note over Engine: 7. Verify proof locally (optional sanity check)

    Engine-->>TX: Proof generated ✅

    Note over TX,Prover: === PROOF GENERATION ENDS ===

    TX->>Engine: populateProvedUnshield(V2_PoseidonMerkle, "Arbitrum", ...)
    Note over Engine: ABI-encode: proof + nullifiers + commitments + recipient
    Engine-->>TX: { to: "0xFA7...", data: "0x(proof+nullifiers+commitments)", value: 0 }

    TX->>TX: Release unshieldMutex
    TX-->>UI: { success: true, transaction: { to, data, value, gasEstimate } }

    User->>ARB: Submit transaction (via Privy sendTransaction)

    Note over ARB: RAILGUN contract verifies:
    Note over ARB: 1. Groth16 proof is valid (pairing check, ~230K gas)
    Note over ARB: 2. Merkle root is current (not stale)
    Note over ARB: 3. Nullifiers haven't been used (no double-spend)
    Note over ARB: 4. If valid: transfer 50 USDC to 0xDEF...
    Note over ARB: 5. Record nullifiers as spent
```

### The mutex — why it exists

```typescript
// transactions.ts line 57
let unshieldMutex: Promise<void> = Promise.resolve();
```

The RAILGUN SDK uses a **single global proof cache**. If two proof generations run concurrently, they overwrite each other's state, producing invalid proofs. The mutex serializes all unshield operations.

---

## 8. Private Transfer Flow — Private → Private

**Private transfer** = send shielded funds to another user's RAILGUN address **without either party revealing their identity**.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Alice as Alice's Browser
    participant TX as transactions.ts
    participant Prover as snarkjs Prover
    participant ARB as Arbitrum

    Alice->>TX: buildPrivateTransfer({ token, amount, recipientRailgunAddress: "0zk1q..." })
    TX->>TX: ensureEngineReady() + ensureProverInitialized()

    TX->>Prover: gasEstimateForUnprovenTransfer(...)
    Prover-->>TX: gasEstimate

    TX->>Prover: generateTransferProof(V2, "Arbitrum", walletId, encKey, ...)
    Note over Prover: Same Groth16 proof as unshield, but:
    Note over Prover: - Output commitments encrypted for RECIPIENT's viewing key
    Note over Prover: - No public address revealed
    Note over Prover: - Memo encrypted inside the commitment

    Prover-->>TX: Proof ready

    TX->>Prover: populateProvedTransfer(...)
    Prover-->>TX: { to: "0xFA7...", data: "0x..." }

    Alice->>ARB: Submit transaction

    Note over ARB: RAILGUN contract:
    Note over ARB: 1. Verify Groth16 proof ✅
    Note over ARB: 2. Record nullifiers (Alice's UTXOs consumed)
    Note over ARB: 3. Insert new commitments (encrypted for Bob)
    Note over ARB: 4. Bob's wallet will find these UTXOs during next scan
```

### What Bob sees:

Bob's RAILGUN wallet periodically scans the Merkle tree. When it finds new commitments that can be decrypted with Bob's viewing key, they appear in Bob's balance. Bob never knows which transaction created them (unless the memo tells him).

